WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.340 --> 00:00:09.500
We're going to move a little bit into the user-facing space now, with ISPF and TSO.

2
00:00:09.500 --> 00:00:16.460
ISPF is the Interactive System Productivity Facility, and TSO is the time-sharing option.

3
00:00:16.460 --> 00:00:23.100
These are two separate products, both of which run on the mainframe in the ZOS operating system.

4
00:00:23.100 --> 00:00:26.380
And a short detour here about acronyms.

5
00:00:26.380 --> 00:00:33.180
We just talked about ISPF, and I told you that it stands for the Interactive System Productivity Facility.

6
00:00:33.500 --> 00:00:40.540
Now, I had to look that up, because I have literally never called it the Interactive System Productivity Facility.

7
00:00:40.540 --> 00:00:48.700
It's always just been ISPF, and you'll probably never hear anybody say time-sharing option either, it's just TSO.

8
00:00:48.700 --> 00:00:53.500
What I'm getting at here is that you shouldn't worry about memorizing what things stand for,

9
00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:56.220
unless they help you remember it, like peachid.

10
00:00:56.220 --> 00:01:01.180
The P in the front of peachid reminds me of the physical channel path identifier.

11
00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:07.660
But you've probably noticed that we go through a lot of acronyms here, and I just don't need to stress about memorizing things.

12
00:01:07.660 --> 00:01:10.380
What's important is what they are.

13
00:01:10.380 --> 00:01:17.260
And ISPF is a full-screen, menu-driven interface which lets you access ZOS tools and utilities.

14
00:01:17.260 --> 00:01:24.620
So, instead of memorizing commands and parameters, you can just navigate to a panel built specifically for the task you want to do,

15
00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:27.020
and enter the options you want.

16
00:01:27.020 --> 00:01:33.900
TSO kind of runs behind ISPF, supporting it, and is typically used for one-word or one-line commands.

17
00:01:33.900 --> 00:01:39.420
So, for most tasks, you've got the option of either doing it through TSO or ISPF.

18
00:01:39.420 --> 00:01:45.740
When you first connect to a mainframe using a terminal emulator, you're greeted by a TSO logon screen.

19
00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:51.020
Top of the screen, you may notice this little slash E at the end of TSO, and you're wondering what that is.

20
00:01:51.020 --> 00:01:56.540
That means it's TSO Extensions, which has a few improvements over the original TSO.

21
00:01:56.540 --> 00:01:59.580
But, again, most people just call it TSO.

22
00:01:59.580 --> 00:02:02.940
You log into TSO with a username and a password.

23
00:02:02.940 --> 00:02:07.580
So, we need to move our cursor over to the User ID field and put in our User ID,

24
00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:11.900
and then there's a password field right over here. Do the same thing with the password.

25
00:02:11.900 --> 00:02:15.660
Many of these fields will be filled out with the default values when you get there,

26
00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:20.060
and if they are, you're probably okay just to leave them like that.

27
00:02:20.060 --> 00:02:22.780
A quick word about navigating to fields.

28
00:02:22.780 --> 00:02:27.340
The easiest way to move from field to field is by hitting the Tab key,

29
00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:30.860
and you can go the other direction by hitting Shift-Tab.

30
00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:34.460
If you try to use your mouse to select the fields you want to type in,

31
00:02:34.460 --> 00:02:39.340
it's real easy to click in the wrong spot, and then you'll wind up putting text where you didn't mean to.

32
00:02:39.340 --> 00:02:43.260
So, for a lot of what we're going to be doing, just use your keyboard.

33
00:02:43.260 --> 00:02:46.460
So, now you've got your User ID and your password in there,

34
00:02:46.460 --> 00:02:49.260
and below that we've got this Procedure field.

35
00:02:49.260 --> 00:02:52.940
This is the procedure that kicks off when you start your TSO session.

36
00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:55.900
This is usually set up for you by someone who knows what they're doing,

37
00:02:55.900 --> 00:03:00.380
so it's best not to change it unless you really need to or someone tells you to.

38
00:03:00.380 --> 00:03:05.740
And even then, make sure you make a note of what it said before in case you need to change it back.

39
00:03:05.740 --> 00:03:08.940
The account number is used to track system usage,

40
00:03:08.940 --> 00:03:14.220
and the Size field determines the amount of memory that your TSO session gets.

41
00:03:14.220 --> 00:03:18.220
Perform is there in case you want to associate your TSO session

42
00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:23.660
with a set of performance characteristics, which can be helpful for WLM.

43
00:03:23.660 --> 00:03:25.020
And then there's Command.

44
00:03:25.020 --> 00:03:28.780
This tells TSO what you want it to do once you're logged in.

45
00:03:28.780 --> 00:03:33.500
You may be prompted to change your password, or you may just feel like changing your password.

46
00:03:33.500 --> 00:03:37.820
To do that, enter your current password in the Password field

47
00:03:37.820 --> 00:03:41.820
and put your new password over in the New Password field.

48
00:03:41.820 --> 00:03:44.700
You will then be prompted to enter the same password again,

49
00:03:44.700 --> 00:03:47.340
just to make sure you typed out what you meant to type.

50
00:03:47.340 --> 00:03:51.020
The Group Identification field can be used to log into another group

51
00:03:51.020 --> 00:03:53.500
and access a different set of resources.

52
00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:58.220
If that's done, it'll typically be done by the Security Administrator.

53
00:03:58.220 --> 00:04:00.460
Then down here, we've got four options.

54
00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:06.460
To select any one of these options, place an S to select it in the space before it.

55
00:04:06.460 --> 00:04:12.540
So if you put an S before NoMail, TSO will suppress the messages intended for you,

56
00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:14.940
specifically during the logon process.

57
00:04:15.900 --> 00:04:17.900
Put an S in front of No Notice,

58
00:04:17.900 --> 00:04:22.060
and that says you don't want to see any of the messages intended for all users.

59
00:04:23.180 --> 00:04:26.540
Next, if you ever accidentally close your terminal window,

60
00:04:26.540 --> 00:04:30.060
there's a chance it'll notice this and close up your session safely.

61
00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:32.860
But if, for whatever reason, you're trying to log in,

62
00:04:32.860 --> 00:04:35.740
and it's telling you your session is already in use,

63
00:04:35.740 --> 00:04:39.820
you can select this and it will reconnect you to that previously running session.

64
00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:42.700
And then there's OID card.

65
00:04:42.700 --> 00:04:46.540
You can use this to enter data using your Operator Identification card,

66
00:04:46.540 --> 00:04:47.500
if you have one of those.

67
00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:50.140
All right, now we're in ISPF.

68
00:04:50.140 --> 00:04:51.500
Let's see what we got.

69
00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:53.580
Up top, we've got the Action Bar.

70
00:04:53.580 --> 00:04:56.940
This works just like a menu in anything else you've ever used.

71
00:04:56.940 --> 00:04:58.220
And then there's a Command Line.

72
00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:00.220
That lets you type out any commands that you know.

73
00:05:00.780 --> 00:05:04.620
This may also be located at the bottom of the screen instead of the top.

74
00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:07.100
Some people like it down there, and they'll set it up that way.

75
00:05:07.820 --> 00:05:10.780
Next, there's this big listing of panel options.

76
00:05:10.780 --> 00:05:14.220
And these show you all the panels that you can go to in ISPF.

77
00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:17.420
So if you want to go to Dialogue Test, for example,

78
00:05:17.420 --> 00:05:20.380
you would put a 7 on the Command Line and then hit Enter,

79
00:05:20.380 --> 00:05:24.860
because 7 is the number on the panel options for Dialogue Test.

80
00:05:25.660 --> 00:05:27.900
At the bottom, there's a listing of function keys.

81
00:05:27.900 --> 00:05:31.820
These remind you of what you can do using the function or F keys on your keyboard.

82
00:05:32.380 --> 00:05:38.540
For example, F7 goes backward and F8 goes forward when you're working on a program or a file

83
00:05:38.540 --> 00:05:40.300
that's bigger than your screen will fit.

84
00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:43.740
Now, if you're looking down at your keyboard and wondering,

85
00:05:43.740 --> 00:05:46.380
what are these function F keys all about?

86
00:05:46.380 --> 00:05:49.580
They're usually in the row above where your numbers are.

87
00:05:49.580 --> 00:05:53.260
And if you don't have that row or they look a little bit different,

88
00:05:53.260 --> 00:05:58.060
you might have to use like a modifier key or remap some of these keys.

89
00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:00.300
But that's something you can explore during the labs.

90
00:06:00.860 --> 00:06:03.660
We also have this dynamic status area.

91
00:06:03.660 --> 00:06:04.860
This area can change.

92
00:06:04.860 --> 00:06:07.980
That's why it's called the dynamic status area.

93
00:06:07.980 --> 00:06:10.780
And it's an area set aside in the panel configuration,

94
00:06:10.780 --> 00:06:13.580
and it's controlled by an ISPF variable.

95
00:06:13.580 --> 00:06:17.420
It's almost always used just to provide you with additional helpful information.

96
00:06:18.460 --> 00:06:19.580
So we're all done now.

97
00:06:19.580 --> 00:06:20.700
How do we disconnect?

98
00:06:20.700 --> 00:06:22.860
There's a couple of ways I'm going to show you too.

99
00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:28.860
You can enter X on the Command Line or you can press F12, the Cancel key.

100
00:06:28.860 --> 00:06:32.620
This will end ISPF and put you back to a TSO Command Line,

101
00:06:32.620 --> 00:06:34.220
because TSO is still running.

102
00:06:34.220 --> 00:06:36.300
It's not the same thing as ISPF.

103
00:06:36.300 --> 00:06:41.420
And if you want to go back into ISPF, just enter the Command ISPF and hit Enter.

104
00:06:41.980 --> 00:06:45.580
To terminate TSO, enter the Command Log Off and hit Enter.

105
00:06:45.580 --> 00:06:48.940
And TSO will cleanly close down and disconnect you.

106
00:06:48.940 --> 00:06:50.780
But don't worry, we'll be back.
